<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-360-694  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 360 694.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 23 1990 v24 n17 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Databases saving face. (use of relational DBMS technology)(SoftTalk)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bozman, Jean S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Relational database vendors are developing more user-friendlyquery interfaces, creating microcomputer-based products that letusers navigate data tables by pointing and clicking and 'masking'the complex query process with SQL commands.andP;  This approachreduces the workload for on-site information systems programmersand eliminates many reporting errors but raises performance andsecurity issues.andP;  New user-friendly databases are not yet provento possess 'industrial strength' and could be easy for intrudersto penetrate if not carefully safeguarded.andP;  Access controls shouldremain tight regardless of how formal the reports are, and usingdata extracts or browsing-only capabilities limits the potentialfor data theft and tampering.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data base management systemsRelational DBMSManagement of EDPSoftware ComplexityUser-FriendlinessQuery ProcessingStructured Query Language.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>